from a short form of   Hildebrand   or any of a variety of other names, male and female, containing ancient Germanic <i>hild</i> ‘battle’ as the first element."],"variants":[{"name":"Hillock","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) small hill’, from Middle English <i>hillok</i>, a diminutive of <i>hille</i> (Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’). See   Hill  ."]},{"name":"Hills","meanings":["English: variant of   Hill   with genitival <i>-s</i> if a relationship name, attested in Matilda <i>Hilles</i>, 1327 (Somerset), where the genitival form may signify widowhood; or with plural <i>-s</i> if habitational, attested in Johanne <i>de Hyles</i>, 1379 (Bickerstaffe, Lancashire), and Ricardo <i>del Hyles</i>, 1379 (Great Eccleston, Lancashire); or, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, probably the most common form."]},{"name":"Hiller","meanings":["German: metronymic from <i>Hille</i>, a pet form of the female personal name <i>Hildegund</i> (see   Hilke  ).","German: from a masculine personal beginning with the ancient Germanic element <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’.","German: variant of <b>Hüller</b> (see   Huller  )."]},{"name":"Hil","meanings":["Altered form of English   Hill  .","Dutch (<b>Van den Hil</b>): topographic name from <i>hil, hul</i> ‘hill’, particularly in the sense of a <i>flight hill</i> above sea level in the southwestern Netherlands."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the 